A. Consider the scalar field g (x, y) = x^2 + y^2. Obtain the minimum of this field using random search, as well as gradient descent with adaptive step, showing the minimum value obtained over the various interactions (mean +/- standard deviation). Compare the minimum curves between the random search and gradient descent considering several starting points.¶

  • Note that the variation of the results for Random Search is notorious, for Gradient Descent it is not possible to see because the method is more accurate.
  • When starting from an interval close to the minimum of the function, both the Gradient Descent method and the Random Search method are able to obtain the result, however starting from high values only the Gradient Descent method comes close.

#random search
# n : number of random trials; loc_x : location of trials x; loc_y : location of trials y; statistics : show progress
def random_search(f,n,loc_x,loc_y,statistics=False):
    #generate random x,y
    x_random = np.random.uniform(*loc_x,n) 
    y_random = np.random.uniform(*loc_y,n)

    if not statistics:
    
        z_random = f(x_random,y_random) #z function generated from random x and y
        return min(z_random)
    
    else:

        #create an array of smaller values
        smaller_z = f(x_random[0],y_random[0])
        minimums = [smaller_z]
        for i in np.arange(1,n):
            if f(x_random[i],y_random[i]) < smaller_z:
                smaller_z = f(x_random[i],y_random[i])
            minimums.append(smaller_z)
        return minimums
    
    
#gradient descent
# n : number of iterations; start : starting point; statistics : show progress
def gradient_descent(f,gf,n,start,learning_rate,statistics=False):
    #starting current value from given start
    curr = np.array(start)
    
    if not statistics:
        #apply gradient method
        for i in np.arange(n):
            prev = curr
            curr = curr - learning_rate * np.array(gf(*prev))

        return f(*curr)
    
    else:
        #apply gradient method storing values in array
        minimums = []
        for i in np.arange(n):
            prev = curr
            curr = curr - learning_rate * np.array(gf(*prev))
            minimums.append(f(*curr))

        return minimums
    
#gradient descent with annealing
def grad_annealing(f,gf,maxsteps=1000,temp_min=.01,loc_x=(-10,10),loc_y=(-10,10),cooling_factor=.95):
    
    #amplitude boundaries and initial temperature
    amp_x = amp_y = loc_x[1]-loc_x[0]
    T = 100*amp_x
    
    #initialize x and y randomly
    x_curr = np.random.uniform(*loc_x)
    y_curr = np.random.uniform(*loc_y)
    cost_curr = f(x_curr,y_curr)
    
    xs,ys,costs = [x_curr],[y_curr],[cost_curr]
    
    #for step in range(int((maxsteps-1)/2)):
    step = 0
    while step < int((maxsteps-1)/2) :
        
        progress = 1 - step/maxsteps
        step+=1                
        T *= cooling_factor # temperature decresses through process
        
        grad = gf(x_curr,y_curr,f)
                
        #move x e y a little and make sure they are still on interval
        x_new = min(loc_x[1],max(x_curr - grad[0] + progress*np.random.uniform(-amp_x/2,amp_x/2),loc_x[0]))
        y_new = min(loc_y[1],max(y_curr - grad[1] + progress*np.random.uniform(-amp_x/2,amp_x/2),loc_y[0]))
        cost_new = f(x_new,y_new)
        
        if (cost_new < cost_curr) or (np.exp((cost_curr-cost_new)/T) > np.random.random()):
            
            x_curr,y_curr,cost_curr = x_new,y_new,cost_new
           
        xs.append(x_curr)
        ys.append(y_curr)
        costs.append(cost_curr)
    
    while step < (maxsteps-1) :
        
        grad = gf(x_curr,y_curr,f)

        x_curr = x_curr - grad[0]*.01
        y_curr = y_curr - grad[1]*.01
        cost_curr = f(x_curr,y_curr)
           
        xs.append(x_curr)
        ys.append(y_curr)
        costs.append(cost_curr)
        
        step+=1
    
    return np.array([xs,ys,costs])

#function f
f = lambda x,y : x**2 + y**2

#gradient of function f
gf = lambda x,y : [2*x,2*y]


#initially, check the progress of the methods in case of
#n = 25 and initial values around 1 with a learning rate of 0.1
# the accounts are repeated 100 times and average and deviation are used

learning_rate,ini,n,rep = 0.1,1,25,100

rep = 100 
random_search_results = np.empty([rep,n])
gradient_descent_results = np.empty([rep,n])

for i in range(rep):
    random_search_results[i,:] = random_search(f,n,[-ini,ini],[-ini,ini],True)
    gradient_descent_results[i,:] = gradient_descent(f,gf,n,[ini,ini],learning_rate,True)

random_search_mean = random_search_results.mean(0)
random_search_std = random_search_results.std(0)

gradient_descent_mean = gradient_descent_results.mean(0)
gradient_descent_std = gradient_descent_results.std(0)

#plot graphics
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
plt.errorbar(np.arange(n),random_search_mean,yerr=random_search_std,color='red',
         label='Random Search\n'+'min: '+str(random_search_mean[-1]))
plt.errorbar(np.arange(n),gradient_descent_mean,yerr=gradient_descent_std,color='blue',
         label = 'Gradient Descent\n'+'min: '+str(gradient_descent_mean[-1]))
plt.xlabel('Step', fontsize = 20)
plt.ylabel('Minimum', fontsize = 20)
plt.xticks(fontsize = 15)
plt.yticks(fontsize = 15)
plt.legend(loc='upper right',fontsize=20)
plt.title("Obtaining minimum: steps with average and deviation",fontsize=30)
plt.show()

B. Let the scalar field g (x, y) = -exp (- ((x-1) ^ 2 + (y1) ^ 2) /0.3^2) -. 5 (exp (-16 ((x-2) ^ 2 (y-2) ^ 2))). Visualize this field as a 3D surface. Apply gradient descent with simulated annealing to try to obtain the absolute minimum of this scalar field. Include identification of an adequate initial temperature, which allows exploration of the two wells, as well as a satisfactory temperature reduction rule. Compare the minimum curve (mean + - standard deviation) between this method and the random search (also presented as mean + - standard deviation).¶

  • The vector field below is interesting for testing the method, as there are two minimum values, one global and one local.
  • When comparing the two methods, it is noted that at the beginning the random search brings better results than the gradient descent with simulated annealing for a small difference, but the descent method with annealing is more effective during the process and it is able to combine the descent of the gradient with the annealing that causes it to reach the global minimum value in counterpoint with the descent of the normal gradient that could reach some local minimum. In the legend of the graph is the final minimum value obtained in the last iteration.

#function f
f = lambda x,y : -np.exp(-((x-1)**2+(y-1)**2)/0.3**2)-1.5*(np.exp(-16*((x-2)**2+(y-2)**2)))

#gradient of generic function
gf = lambda x,y,g,d=.01: [ (g(x+d,y)-g(x-d,y))/(2*d) + 1e-30 , (g(x,y+d)-g(x,y-d))/(2*d) + 1e-30 ]

rep = 10
n = 10000
loc=(-10,10)

grad_annealing_results = np.empty([rep,n])
random_search_results = np.empty([rep,n])

for i in range(rep):
    grad_annealing_results[i,:] = grad_annealing(f,gf,maxsteps=n,loc_x=loc,loc_y=loc,temp_min=1e-4)[-1]
    random_search_results[i,:] = random_search(f,n,loc,loc,True)

#get samples to plot    
step = 100

grad_annealing_mean = grad_annealing_results.mean(0)[0::step]
grad_annealing_std = grad_annealing_results.std(0)[0::step]

random_search_mean = random_search_results.mean(0)[0::step]
random_search_std = random_search_results.std(0)[0::step]

#plot graph
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
plt.errorbar(np.arange(0,n,step),random_search_mean,yerr=random_search_std,color='red',
         label='Random Search\n'+'min: '+str(random_search_mean[-1]),alpha=0.5)
plt.errorbar(np.arange(0,n,step),grad_annealing_mean,yerr=grad_annealing_std,color='blue',
         label='Gradient Annealing\n'+'min: '+str(grad_annealing_mean[-1]),alpha=0.5)

C. For each of the two cases above, identify all the parameters involved and justify the respective configuration choices.¶

  • Most parameter choices are made by trial and error, but there are some subtleties.
  • In the gradient descent part, there is the learning rate, which is the value by which the gradient is multiplied to add to the current value of the function, I used the value 0.1 so that it is able to perform the descent. The value cannot be too high not to vary more than the function varies, nor too low for the iterations to take effect and the computational cost to perform the accounts is not too great.
  • In the part of the gradient descent with annealing, there is the same learning proportional to the gradient as in the previous item, however a random number is also added so that there is a variation of the direction and the method does not just follow the direction of the gradient, being able to vary one little. Note here that the random number cannot be too big or too small for the method to be effective, so I add to the gradient a random number that looks for an amplitude of 1/4 of the interval centered on the point, in addition to ensuring that it is within the sought range.
  • The method of gradient descent with annealing also depends on the choice of method with which the temperature decreases with each iteration, which must be a function that decreases with time, therefore I use an initial value of 100 times the amplitude sought (chosen by trial and error) and multiply the temperature by 0.95 with each iteration so that it decreases.
  • Note that it is these choices of temperature and decreasing the random number over time that allow the method at the beginning to vary more and not fall into a local minimum and at the end decrease to the minimum possible value during the descent of the global minimum found. The result here was good, but it was a lot of work to define these parameters and functions and there was a large human labor cost for that, which makes it more susceptible to any eventual error.
